{"id": "6", "question": "The team represented by the scarf in the picture defeated a certain team 2:0 in 2023. In that match, in the first half, someone's long-range shot from outside the box was saved, and then someone's header at the far post, while unmarked, unfortunately went over the bar. In the second half, someone scored with a powerful shot, but the goal was disallowed due to a handball. In this match, what was the jersey number of the defender marking the goal scorer for the second valid goal?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: 中超集锦：青岛海牛vs梅州客家，陈纯新闲庭信步，连过3人精彩进球 - YouTube\nPAGE_TEXT: 中超集锦：青岛海牛vs梅州客家，陈纯新闲庭信步，连过3人精彩进球 - YouTube About Press Copyright Contact us Creator Advertise Developers Terms Privacy Policy & Safety How YouTube works Test new features © 2026 Google LLC", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_0", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}], "stats": {"n_source_urls": 1, "n_image_urls": 1, "n_observations": 1}}
{"id": "14", "question": "The picture was taken inside a shopping mall. About 1 kilometre directly north of the mall there is a historic landmark where a national leader delivered a lengthy speech in June 1987. From the speaker’s own perspective, and listing the flags on the speaker’s right-hand side from closest to furthest (inner to outer), what were the three flags in order?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: Google Maps\nPAGE_TEXT: Google Maps When you have eliminated the JavaScript , whatever remains must be an empty page. Enable JavaScript to see Google Maps.", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_0", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: \"Tear Down This Wall\" - Ronald Reagan at the Brandenburg Gate - AlliiertenMuseum\nPAGE_TEXT: \"Tear Down This Wall\" - Ronald Reagan at the Brandenburg Gate - AlliiertenMuseum This website uses cookies. For more information on this and on your rights as a user of the website see our Privacy Notice at the bottom of the page. Click on “I agree” in order to accept cookies and use our website immediately. Necessary cookies only I agree Skip to Content Skip to Footer DE EN FR Contrast Sign language Easy language Search Search Search Museum Overview The Latest Information About us Exhibitions Overview Permanent Exhibition Special Exhibition Outdoor Exhibition Past Temporary Exhibitions Events Educational services Overview Adults Schools Teachers Families Inclusive programs Digital programs Publications Multimedia guide Collection Overview Object in focus Your object Collection online Topics Overview The Berlin Airlift The Second Berlin Crisis Denazification The term “Allies“ “Cold War” – History of a term The Korean War (1950-1953) Search for: Special opening hours on public holidays 3.4. – 6.4. open 24. – 25.5. open Tickets Admission free of charge Getting here AlliiertenMuseum Clayallee 135 14195 Berlin Free parking is available. Metro: U3 to “Oskar-Helene-Heim” Bus: Line 115 or X83 to “AlliiertenMuseum” Google Maps Contact +49 (0)30/8181990 info@alliiertenmuseum.de Exhibitions Temporary exhibition \"Tear Down This Wall\" June 12, 2007 - December 31, 2007 “Tear Down This Wall” – Ronald Reagan at the Brandenburg Gate June 12th of this year will be the twentieth anniversary of the day when President Ronald Reagan spoke at the then impassable Brandenburg Gate and made a direct appeal to Soviet general secretary Mikhail Gorbachev to tear down the Berlin Wall. At the time, most of us dismissed this appeal as a bit of show business – Ronald Reagan wanted to emulate John F. Kennedy and go down in history with a Berlin quotation. Three years later, matters looked quite different, and Reagan’s words had become a familiar catchphrase throughout the world. To refresh our memories: On November 9, 1989 the Berlin Wall opened, and one year later Germany was unified. Only one year after that, the once mighty Soviet Union was no more. The Allied Museum is taking the twentieth anniversary as an opportunity to recall the speech and the speaker. What was the actual occasion for this speech? Against which backdrop of Berlin’s German and international history must we view the US president’s speech? And how did he arrive at that famous phrase? The exhibition offers information to help us find the answers to these and similar questions. From the beginning, US president Ronald Reagan was viewed as an enemy by the peace movement that formed in the early 1980s and opposed the NATO dual-track decision. On the evening before the speech some 20,000 people demonstrated in the center of West-Berlin. Unfortunately, the demonstration ended in street battles with the police, which no longer had anything to do with the actual occasion for the protests. Twenty years later, we have the opportunity to reexamine the perspectives of that time in the light of what we know now. The exhibition presents objects and documents as well as film and photographic material and was made possible by generous loans. The primary lender was the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library in Simi Valley, California, which kindly opened its archives and placed important exhibits at our disposal. It is to American and German museums, a number of public and private collections and archives as well as many contemporary witnesses from Washington, Los Angeles, Berlin, Bonn and other places that we owe the large number of objects on loan. The exhibition is accompanied by a publication bringing together contributions by contemporary witnesses and experts. As always at the Allied Museum, the texts can be read in German, English and French. We are rather proud that then Federal President Richard von Weizsäcker and Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl have contributed words of greeting to the exhibition, th", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_1", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: \"Tear Down this Wall\" Berlin Wall Speech - President Reagan's Address at the Brandenburg Gate - YouTube\nPAGE_TEXT: \"Tear Down this Wall\" Berlin Wall Speech - President Reagan's Address at the Brandenburg Gate - YouTube About Press Copyright Contact us Creator Advertise Developers Terms Privacy Policy & Safety How YouTube works Test new features © 2026 Google LLC", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_2", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}], "stats": {"n_source_urls": 3, "n_image_urls": 1, "n_observations": 3}}
