{"id": "1065", "question": "This figure is from a paper published on arXiv. One of the authors has the initials KK. He submitted another paper to arXiv on May 22, 2024. In the first figure on page thirteen of that other paper, what is the maximum value of the x-axis?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation\nPAGE_TEXT: Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation I Introduction II Starobinsky inflation III One-Loop Corrections from Inflaton Self-Interactions IV One-Loop Corrections from Inflaton Couplings to Fermions IV.1 Yukawa interaction with the inflaton IV.1.1 Massless fermion m f = 0 m_{f}=0 IV.1.2 Massive fermion m f ≠ 0 m_{f}\\neq 0 IV.2 Yukawa interaction in the Jordan frame V One-Loop Corrections from Inflaton Couplings to Scalars V.1 Trilinear coupling to the inflaton V.1.1 Massless scalar m s = 0 m_{s}=0 V.1.2 Massive scalar: m s ≠ 0 m_{s}\\neq 0 V.2 Scalar coupling in the Jordan frame VI Effects of Supersymmetry VII Summary and Conclusions Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation John Ellis a,b John.Ellis@cern.ch Tony Gherghetta c tgher@umn.edu Kunio Kaneta d kaneta@ed.niigata-u.ac.jp Wenqi Ke c,e wke@umn.edu Keith A. Olive c,e olive@umn.edu a Department of Physics, King’s College London, Strand, London, WC2R 2LS, UK b Theoretical Physics Department, CERN, Geneva, Switzerland c School of Physics and Astronomy, University of Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN 55455, USA d Faculty of Education, Niigata University, Niigata 950-2181, Japan e William I. Fine Theoretical Physics Institute, School of Physics and Astronomy, University of Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN 55455, USA (October 16, 2025) Abstract We analyze radiative corrections to the Starobinsky model of inflation arising from self-interactions of the inflaton, and from its Yukawa couplings, y y , to matter fermions, and dimensionful trilinear couplings, κ \\kappa , to scalar fields, which could be responsible for reheating the Universe after inflation. The inflaton self-interactions are found to be of higher order in the Hubble expansion rate during inflation, and hence unimportant for CMB observations. In contrast, matter couplings to the Starobinsky inflaton can have significant effects on the spectral index of scalar CMB perturbations, n s n_{s} , and on the tensor-to-scalar ratio, r r . Using a renormalization-group improved analysis of the effective inflationary potential, we find that the Planck measurement of n s n_{s} constrains the inflaton coupling to light fermions in the Einstein frame: y < 4.5 × 10 − 4 y<4.5\\times 10^{-4} , corresponding to an upper limit on the reheating temperature T RH < 2 × 10 11 T_{\\rm RH}<2\\times 10^{11} GeV, whereas the ACT DR6 measurement of n s n_{s} corresponds to 3.8 × 10 − 4 < y < 5.6 × 10 − 4 3.8\\times 10^{-4}<y<5.6\\times 10^{-4} and 1.7 × 10 11 ​ GeV < T RH < 2.8 × 10 11 1.7\\times 10^{11}~{\\rm GeV}<T_{\\rm RH}<2.8\\times 10^{11} GeV, while the upper limits on r r provide weaker constraints. Planck data also imply a constraint on a trilinear inflaton coupling to light scalars in the Einstein frame: κ ≤ 4 × 10 12 \\kappa\\leq 4\\times 10^{12} GeV, corresponding to T RH ≤ 4.2 × 10 13 T_{\\rm RH}\\leq 4.2\\times 10^{13} GeV. We further present constraints on inflaton couplings to massive fermions and scalars, and analyze constraints on couplings in the Jordan frame. † † preprint: UMN–TH–4511/25, FTPI–MINN–25/13, KCL–PH–TH/2025–39, CERN–TH–2025–198 I Introduction Until recently, data on perturbations Planck in the cosmic microwave background (CMB) have been strikingly consistent with the original model of inflation formulated by Starobinsky Staro as an R 2 R^{2} deformation of the minimal Einstein-Hilbert action, which could be reformulated WhittStelle ; Kalara:1990ar , as the minimal action supplemented by a scalar field with a characteristic tree-level potential V = 3 4 ​ m 2 ​ M P 2 ​ [ 1 − e − 2 3 ​ ϕ M P ] 2 , V\\;=\\;\\frac{3}{4}m^{2}M_{P}^{2}\\left[1-e^{-\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{3}}\\frac{\\phi}{M_{P}}}\\right]^{2}\\,, (1) where the reduced Planck mass M P = 8 ​ π / G N = 2.435 × 10 18 M_{P}=\\sqrt{8\\pi/G_{N}}=2.435\\times 10^{18} GeV. From this potential, it is straightforward to compute the tilt of the scalar anisotropy spectrum, n s ≃ 0.965 n_{s}\\simeq 0.965 , and a tensor-to-scalar ratio of r ≃ 0.0035 r\\simeq 0.0035 , with a slight depen", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_0", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: [2510.15137] Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation\nPAGE_TEXT: [2510.15137] Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation Skip to main content Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit. We gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, member institutions , and all contributors. Donate > hep-ph > arXiv:2510.15137 Help | Advanced Search All fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text Search open search GO open navigation menu quick links Login Help Pages About --> High Energy Physics - Phenomenology arXiv:2510.15137 (hep-ph) [Submitted on 16 Oct 2025] Title: Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation Authors: John Ellis , Tony Gherghetta , Kunio Kaneta , Wenqi Ke , Keith A. Olive View a PDF of the paper titled Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation, by John Ellis and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: We analyze radiative corrections to the Starobinsky model of inflation arising from self-interactions of the inflaton, and from its Yukawa couplings, $y$, to matter fermions, and dimensionful trilinear couplings, $\\kappa$, to scalar fields, which could be responsible for reheating the Universe after inflation. The inflaton self-interactions are found to be of higher order in the Hubble expansion rate during inflation, and hence unimportant for CMB observations. In contrast, matter couplings to the Starobinsky inflaton can have significant effects on the spectral index of scalar CMB perturbations, $n_s$, and on the tensor-to-scalar ratio, $r$. Using a renormalization-group improved analysis of the effective inflationary potential, we find that the Planck measurement of $n_s$ constrains the inflaton coupling to light fermions in the Einstein frame: $y < 4.5 \\times 10^{-4}$, corresponding to an upper limit on the reheating temperature $T_{\\rm RH} < 2 \\times 10^{11}~{\\rm GeV}$, whereas the ACT DR6 measurement of $n_s$ corresponds to $3.8 \\times 10^{-4} < y < 5.6 \\times 10^{-4}$ and $1.7 \\times 10^{11} ~{\\rm GeV} < T_{\\rm RH} < 2.8 \\times 10^{11}~{\\rm GeV}$, while the upper limits on $r$ provide weaker constraints. Planck data also imply a constraint on a trilinear inflaton coupling to light scalars in the Einstein frame: $\\kappa \\leq 4 \\times 10^{12}~{\\rm GeV}$, corresponding to $T_{\\rm RH} \\leq 4.2 \\times 10^{13}~{\\rm GeV}$. We further present constraints on inflaton couplings to massive fermions and scalars, and analyze constraints on couplings in the Jordan frame. Comments: 15 pages, 14 figures Subjects: High Energy Physics - Phenomenology (hep-ph) ; Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics (astro-ph.CO); General Relativity and Quantum Cosmology (gr-qc); High Energy Physics - Theory (hep-th) Report number: UMN-TH-4511/25, FTPI-MINN-25/13, KCL-PH-TH/2025-39, CERN-TH-2025-198 Cite as: arXiv:2510.15137 [hep-ph] (or arXiv:2510.15137v1 [hep-ph] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2510.15137 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Wenqi Ke [ view email ] [v1] Thu, 16 Oct 2025 20:54:58 UTC (572 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Effects of Radiative Corrections on Starobinsky Inflation, by John Ellis and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: hep-ph < prev | next > new | recent | 2025-10 Change to browse by: astro-ph astro-ph.CO gr-qc hep-th References & Citations INSPIRE HEP NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( What is the Explorer? ) Connected Papers Toggle Connected Papers ( What is Connected Papers? ) Litmaps Toggle Litmaps ( What is Litmaps? ) scite.ai Toggle scite Smart Citations ( What are Smart Citations? ) Code, Data, Media Code, Data and Medi", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_1", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: [2405.13402] Accelerating universe at early and late times in extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity\nPAGE_TEXT: [2405.13402] Accelerating universe at early and late times in extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity Skip to main content Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit. We gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, member institutions , and all contributors. Donate > astro-ph > arXiv:2405.13402 Help | Advanced Search All fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text Search open search GO open navigation menu quick links Login Help Pages About --> Astrophysics > Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics arXiv:2405.13402 (astro-ph) [Submitted on 22 May 2024 ( v1 ), last revised 12 Jul 2024 (this version, v2)] Title: Accelerating universe at early and late times in extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity Authors: Kunio Kaneta , Kin-ya Oda , Motohiko Yoshimura View a PDF of the paper titled Accelerating universe at early and late times in extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity, by Kunio Kaneta and 2 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: We propose a scenario that can explain the early-time inflation and the late-time dark energy within a unified framework. A scalar potential combining power-law and exponential type in a context of extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity is critically important for this realization. A realistic scenario can be achieved in a two-field model in which one directional motion in field space realizes the slow-roll inflation. The inflaton ends up with oscillatory period and turns its direction to another direction that is identified as the quintessence field, giving rise to the dark energy at late times. The inflaton oscillation is expected to realize efficient heating if parametric amplification works. Along the quintessence direction, the present universe is on the way to reach the asymptotic fixed point. We search for successful parameter region, taking potential function in the form of low-order field powers times decreasing exponential in two dimensional field space. Comments: 21 pages, 12 figures, Version accepted for publication in Physical Review D Subjects: Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics (astro-ph.CO) ; General Relativity and Quantum Cosmology (gr-qc); High Energy Physics - Phenomenology (hep-ph) Cite as: arXiv:2405.13402 [astro-ph.CO] (or arXiv:2405.13402v2 [astro-ph.CO] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2405.13402 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Kunio Kaneta [ view email ] [v1] Wed, 22 May 2024 07:21:54 UTC (2,583 KB) [v2] Fri, 12 Jul 2024 11:33:58 UTC (2,588 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Accelerating universe at early and late times in extended Jordan-Brans-Dicke gravity, by Kunio Kaneta and 2 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: astro-ph.CO < prev | next > new | recent | 2024-05 Change to browse by: astro-ph gr-qc hep-ph References & Citations INSPIRE HEP NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted 