{"id": "1114", "question": "The provided image is from a paper published on the arXiv website. The first author of this paper, abbreviated as AA, published another paper submitted on November 7, 2025, and last revised on November 10, 2025. In that second paper, in the image above Figure 2, what is the leftmost English word in the bottommost dashed box?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems\nPAGE_TEXT: Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems I Introduction & Related Work I-A Why Gate-based QAOA over Quantum Annealing? I-B Our Contribution II Methodology II-A Stage 1 — Low-rank dictionary learning II-B Stage 2 — Performance-driven importance scores II-C Stage 3 — Five-qubit QUBO and depth-3 QAOA II-D Stage 4 — Quantum semi-Random Forest (QsRF) II-E Complexity remarks II-F Computational Complexity & Runtime II-G Datasets: ICM–150 and ICM–500 III Results and Discussion III-A Dictionary Quality and Sparsity III-B QAOA Energy Landscape III-C End-to-End Recommendation Accuracy III-D User-Level Versus Global Ranking Quality III-E Generalisation to ICM–500 III-F Runtime Analysis III-G Key Takeaways III-H User–level versus global ranking quality IV Conclusion V Future Work Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems Azadeh Alavi1, Fatemeh Kouchmeshki2, Abdolrahman Alavi2, Yongli Ren1, Jiayang Niu1 First and second authors contributed equally to this work 1RMIT University, Melbourne, Australia Email: {azadeh.alavi, yongli.ren, s4068570}@rmit.edu.au 2Pattern Recognition Pty. Ltd., Melbourne, Australia Email: {admin@pr2aid.com, rahmanalavi1944@gmail.com} Abstract Modern recommenders describe each item with hundreds of sparse semantic tags, yet most quantum pipelines still map one qubit per tag, demanding well beyond one hundred qubits, far out of reach for current noisy-intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) devices and prone to deep, error-amplifying circuits. We close this gap with a three-stage hybrid machine learning algorithm that compresses tag profiles, optimizes feature selection under a fixed qubit budget via QAOA, and scores recommendations with a Quantum semi-Random Forest (QsRF) built on just five qubits, while performing similarly to the state-of-the-art methods. Leveraging SVD sketching and k-means, we learn a 1 000-atom dictionary ( > > > 97 % variance), then solve a 20×20 QUBO via depth-3 QAOA to select 5 atoms. A 100-tree QsRF trained on these codes matches full-feature baselines on ICM-150/500. Index Terms: Recommender systems, Dictionary Learning, QAOA, Bagged trees, Quantum machine learning, hybrid machine learning I Introduction & Related Work Modern content platforms such as Netflix , Amazon and TikTok describe every item with hundreds of sparse semantic tags. Identifying the smallest subset that preserves ranking quality is NP–hard, and naïvely mapping one qubit to one tag quickly surpasses the limits of Noisy-Intermediate-Scale-Quantum (NISQ) hardware. To compress this combinatorial explosion, recent hybrid pipelines formulate feature selection as a Q uadratic U nconstrained B inary O ptimisation (QUBO) and delegate the search to quantum annealers [ 1 , 2 ] or shallow gate-based circuits [ 3 ] . Nevertheless, the entire 150-tag space in the smallest QuantumCLEF split is still embedded onto hardware with limited connectivity, leading to deep, error-prone circuits. Historically, recommender systems relied on dense latent factor models whose dimensions are hard to interpret. In contrast, dictionary learning provides compact and inherently sparse representations. Early large-scale work by Mensch et al. [ 4 ] introduced a K–SVD-style factorisation that scales to terabyte user–item matrices, while Kartoglu and Spratling [ 5 ] demonstrated that structured sparse coding can rival dense baselines in both rating prediction and top- N N italic_N ranking with far fewer parameters. Such results suggest that a well-chosen set of interpretable atoms can replace raw tags without sacrificing accuracy—an observation we exploit before invoking quantum search. Quantum feature selection has so far moved along two strands. On the one hand, mutual-information and counterfactual criteria have been encoded directly into QUBO matrices and solved with either quantum annealing or the Quantum Approximate Optimisation Algorithm (QAOA) [ 6 , 7 , 2 ] . On the other hand, recursive variants such as ", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_0", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: [2508.00027] Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems\nPAGE_TEXT: [2508.00027] Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems Skip to main content Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit. We gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, member institutions , and all contributors. Donate > quant-ph > arXiv:2508.00027 Help | Advanced Search All fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text Search open search GO open navigation menu quick links Login Help Pages About --> Quantum Physics arXiv:2508.00027 (quant-ph) [Submitted on 30 Jul 2025] Title: Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems Authors: Azadeh Alavi , Fatemeh Kouchmeshki , Abdolrahman Alavi , Yongli Ren , Jiayang Niu View a PDF of the paper titled Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems, by Azadeh Alavi and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: Modern recommenders describe each item with hundreds of sparse semantic tags, yet most quantum pipelines still map one qubit per tag, demanding well beyond one hundred qubits, far out of reach for current noisy-intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) devices and prone to deep, error-amplifying circuits. We close this gap with a three-stage hybrid machine learning algorithm that compresses tag profiles, optimizes feature selection under a fixed qubit budget via QAOA, and scores recommendations with a Quantum semi-Random Forest (QsRF) built on just five qubits, while performing similarly to the state-of-the-art methods. Leveraging SVD sketching and k-means, we learn a 1000-atom dictionary ($>$97 \\% variance), then solve a 2020 QUBO via depth-3 QAOA to select 5 atoms. A 100-tree QsRF trained on these codes matches full-feature baselines on ICM-150/500. Comments: Submitted to IEEE Quantum AI Conference (QAI 2025), awaiting peer review Subjects: Quantum Physics (quant-ph) ; Machine Learning (cs.LG) Cite as: arXiv:2508.00027 [quant-ph] (or arXiv:2508.00027v1 [quant-ph] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2508.00027 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Azadeh Alavi [ view email ] [v1] Wed, 30 Jul 2025 03:20:44 UTC (310 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Quantum Semi-Random Forests for Qubit-Efficient Recommender Systems, by Azadeh Alavi and 4 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: quant-ph < prev | next > new | recent | 2025-08 Change to browse by: cs cs.LG References & Citations INSPIRE HEP NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( What is the Explorer? ) Connected Papers Toggle Connected Papers ( What is Connected Papers? ) Litmaps Toggle Litmaps ( What is Litmaps? ) scite.ai Toggle scite Smart Citations ( What are Smart Citations? ) Code, Data, Media Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article alphaXiv Toggle alphaXiv ( What is alphaXiv? ) Links to Code Toggle CatalyzeX Code Finder for Papers ( What is CatalyzeX? ) DagsHub Toggle DagsHub ( What is