{"id": "1132", "question": "The image shows a scenic spot in a province in China. In 2024, a district within this province saw its regional Gross Domestic Product (GDP) grow by 5.6% year-on-year, calculated at comparable prices. Xinhua Net published an article in April 2023 about a rapeseed flower festival held in this area. In the second photo of the article, there is a sign in front of the people. Among the yellow Chinese characters on this sign, what is the second character from the right?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: 山东兖州“以花为媒”推进乡村振兴新路径-新华网\nPAGE_TEXT: 山东兖州“以花为媒”推进乡村振兴新路径-新华网 新华网 > 新华网城市 > 正文 2023 04 / 03 10:35:27 来源：新华财经 山东兖州“以花为媒”推进乡村振兴新路径 字体： 小 中 大 分享到： 山东兖州“以花为媒”推进乡村振兴新路径 2023-04-03 10:35:27 来源：新华财经 4月1日，山东省济宁市兖州区牛楼小镇千亩油菜花观赏田遍地金黄处处芬芳，第五届油菜花节暨“乡村好时节，端信有礼·霓裳九州文化节”正式开幕，活动现场人头攒动，在鼓乐声中十二花神相继入场，汉风舞蹈、汉服走秀等古风表演精彩纷呈，引得前来赏花观景的游客络绎不绝。 鼓乐声中十二花神相继入场 康岩摄 本次油菜花文化旅游节策划推出了“游赏千亩油菜花”“巨型稻草人王国”“汉服T台走秀”“诗词展演”“沉浸式舞台剧”“移风易俗集体婚礼”“非遗文创市集”等十余项主题活动，分片区、分日程开展，让游客们在享受田园乡村美景的同时，游览巨型稻草人，体验童趣游乐项目，增加游客参与感，满足不同年龄层次的游客需求。设置古风表演，以集市和流动摊铺的形式，将乡村特色商品、非遗文创产品进行展示展销，向游客展示非物质文化遗产的魅力，在契合中华民族传统文化的同时，又充满新时代文明向上的气息。 兖州第五届油菜花节启动 康岩摄 为充分满足旅游消费需求，本次活动特地引入50余种具有地方特色的餐饮美食，为广大市民和游客带来一场饕餮盛宴。同时，在花海内设置了现下热门的房车基地、露营野餐、田园研学等“网红”活动区域，广大市民和游客朋友在赏花踏青之时，获得更新鲜、更多元的休闲体验。 花海彩田中游客络绎不绝 康岩摄 兖州区抢抓济宁市泗河绿色发展带重点建设和兖州区泗河全域开发整治打造“3+1”四大板块的机遇，先行先试，在辖区泗河堤内，以休闲农业和便民康养为抓手，以文化体验和旅游观光为切入点，打造了花海彩田、马桥湿地融合发展的生态宜居休憩地。项目建成后，先后承办了济宁市庆祝建国70周年文艺晚会、兖州区第29届农民文化艺术节等，举办了4届牛楼花海彩田新春大庙会、花灯展、向日葵节、国庆游园会等30余项大型系列活动，已发展为辐射涵盖周边60公里的半小时生活圈、一小时城际圈，极大丰富了群众的精神文化生活。 万亩油菜花田成为网红打卡地 康岩摄 2019年以来，兖州区已连续举办了五届油菜花节，以花为媒，以节扬名，将油菜花节与统筹城乡发展、乡村旅游相结合，打造了生态休闲农业，培育了新农村特色产业，积极探索推进乡村振兴新模式、新业态、新路径。 据了解，兖州区将继续围绕泗河景观带，以“一心连三点，一廊串五区”为引领，新建牛楼小镇二期——牛楼民俗风情街、济宁航天科普研学博览基地、乡村振兴培训中心学员公寓、牛楼社会养老院等项目，着力夯实产业之基，多方协调消除困境，全面提升乡村振兴齐鲁样板的示范性和引领性。（张美荣 李海波） 【纠错】 【责任编辑:郭香玉】 深度观察 融媒集萃 山东兖州“以花为媒”推进乡村振兴新路径", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_2", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}], "stats": {"n_source_urls": 3, "n_image_urls": 1, "n_observations": 1}}
{"id": "1139", "question": "This image is from a paper published on arXiv, where one of the authors has the initials SC. This author also submitted another paper to arXiv on November 27, 2024. In Figure 2 on page 10 of that other paper, what is the color of the point that is higher than all other colors at the maximum value on the y-axis?", "observations": [{"text": "PAGE_TITLE: Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments\nPAGE_TEXT: Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments I Introduction II CEvNS Cross Section and Form Factors III Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments IV Analyzing Standard and Beyond the Standard Model Signals IV.1 Precision Measurement of the Weak Mixing Angle IV.2 Probing Neutrino Electromagnetic Properties IV.2.1 Neutrino Magnetic Moment IV.2.2 Neutrino Charge Radius IV.3 Sensitivity to Neutrino Non-Standard Interactions V Conclusions \\UseRawInputEncoding Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments S. Carey samcarey@wayne.edu Department of Physics and Astronomy, Wayne State University, Detroit, Michigan 48201, USA V. Pandey vpandey@fnal.gov Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory, Batavia, Illinois 60510, USA Abstract Coherent elastic neutrino–nucleus scattering (CEvNS) provides a powerful framework for testing the Standard Model (SM) and searching for new physics at low energies. In this work, we examine the prospects for argon-based CEvNS experiments at stopped-pion sources to perform precision measurements of weak interactions and probe non-standard neutrino properties. Our study focused on the CENNS-10 and CENNS-750 detectors at the Spallation Neutron Source at Oak Ridge National Laboratory, the Coherent Captain Mills (CCM) detector at Los Alamos National Laboratory, and the proposed PIP2-BD detector at Fermilab’s Facility for Dark Matter Discovery (F2D2). Using realistic neutrino fluxes and detector configurations corresponding to these facilities, we evaluate event rates and sensitivities to a range of observables. Within the SM, argon-based CEvNS detectors enable precision tests of electroweak parameters, including the weak mixing angle, at momentum transfers well below the electroweak scale. We also investigate the sensitivity of these experiments to neutrino electromagnetic properties, such as the magnetic moment and effective charge radius, as well as to possible non-standard neutrino interactions with quarks. Together, these studies highlight the potential of argon-based CEvNS experiments as a clean and versatile platform for precision exploration of non-standard neutrino properties. † † preprint: FERMILAB-PUB-25-0748-PPD, WSU-HEP-2502 I Introduction The study of neutrino interactions with nuclei has long served as a critical avenue for advancing both particle physics and astrophysics Formaggio and Zeller ( 2012 ); Balasi et al. ( 2015 ) . Among these processes, coherent elastic neutrino-nucleus scattering (CEvNS) occupies a special place. First predicted in the mid-1970s as a direct consequence of the Standard Model (SM) Freedman ( 1974 ); Drukier and Stodolsky ( 1984 ) , CEvNS arises when a neutrino scatters coherently off an entire nucleus, leading to an enhanced cross section that scales approximately with the square of the neutron number. Despite its relatively large predicted cross section compared to other low-energy neutrino processes, the detection of CEvNS proved elusive for more than four decades due to the tiny nuclear recoil energies, typically of order tens of keV, that must be measured Scholberg ( 2006 ) . This challenge was overcome in 2017, when the COHERENT collaboration reported the first observation of CEvNS using a CsI detector at the Spallation Neutron Source Akimov et al. ( 2017 ) . Subsequent measurements with additional detector technologies Aguilar-Arevalo et al. ( 2022a ); Colaresi et al. ( 2021 ); Akimov et al. ( 2022a ); Ackermann et al. ( 2025 ); Adamski et al. ( 2025 ) , including liquid argon Akimov et al. ( 2021a ) , have strengthened this discovery and expanded the physics reach of CEvNS. The achievement represented not only a milestone in confirming a long-standing SM prediction, but also the opening of a new experimental frontier for precision neutrino physics at low energies. The physics potential of CEvNS stems from its unique sensitivity to both SM parameters and possible signatures of new physics. ", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_0", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: [2510.14015] Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments\nPAGE_TEXT: [2510.14015] Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments Skip to main content Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit. We gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, member institutions , and all contributors. Donate > hep-ph > arXiv:2510.14015 Help | Advanced Search All fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text Search open search GO open navigation menu quick links Login Help Pages About --> High Energy Physics - Phenomenology arXiv:2510.14015 (hep-ph) [Submitted on 15 Oct 2025] Title: Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments Authors: Sam Carey , Vishvas Pandey View a PDF of the paper titled Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments, by Sam Carey and Vishvas Pandey View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: Coherent elastic neutrino-nucleus scattering (CEvNS) provides a powerful framework for testing the Standard Model (SM) and searching for new physics at low energies. In this work, we examine the prospects for argon-based CEvNS experiments at stopped-pion sources to perform precision measurements of weak interactions and probe non-standard neutrino properties. Our study focused on the CENNS-10 and CENNS-750 detectors at the Spallation Neutron Source at Oak Ridge National Laboratory, the Coherent Captain Mills (CCM) detector at Los Alamos National Laboratory, and the proposed PIP2-BD detector at Fermilabs Facility for Dark Matter Discovery (F2D2). Using realistic neutrino fluxes and detector configurations corresponding to these facilities, we evaluate event rates and sensitivities to a range of observables. Within the SM, argon-based CEvNS detectors enable precision tests of electroweak parameters, including the weak mixing angle, at momentum transfers well below the electroweak scale. We also investigate the sensitivity of these experiments to neutrino electromagnetic properties, such as the magnetic moment and effective charge radius, as well as to possible non-standard neutrino interactions with quarks. Together, these studies highlight the potential of argon-based CEvNS experiments as a clean and versatile platform for precision exploration of non-standard neutrino properties. Comments: 15 pages, 12 figures Subjects: High Energy Physics - Phenomenology (hep-ph) ; High Energy Physics - Experiment (hep-ex) Cite as: arXiv:2510.14015 [hep-ph] (or arXiv:2510.14015v1 [hep-ph] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2510.14015 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Sam Carey [ view email ] [v1] Wed, 15 Oct 2025 18:49:52 UTC (1,350 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Prospects for Exploring Non-Standard Neutrino Properties with Argon-Based CEvNS Experiments, by Sam Carey and Vishvas Pandey View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: hep-ph < prev | next > new | recent | 2025-10 Change to browse by: hep-ex References & Citations INSPIRE HEP NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( What is the Explorer? ) Connected Papers Toggle Connected Papers ( What is Connected Papers? ) Litmaps Toggle Litmaps ( What is Litmaps? ) scite.ai Toggle scite Smart Citations ( What are Smart Citations? ) Code, Data, Media Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article alphaXiv Toggle alphaXiv ( What is alphaXiv? ) Links to Code Toggle CatalyzeX Code Finder for Papers ( What is CatalyzeX? ) DagsHub Toggle DagsHub ( What is DagsHub? ) GotitPub Toggle Gotit.pub ( What is GotitPub? ) Huggingface Toggle Hugging Face ( What is Huggingface? ) Scie", "source_type": "tool_output_text", "channel_id": "source_1", "session_idx": 1, "role": "tool"}, {"text": "PAGE_TITLE: [2412.19810] Quasielastic Lepton-Nucleus Scattering and the Correlated Fermi Gas Model\nPAGE_TEXT: [2412.19810] Quasielastic Lepton-Nucleus Scattering and the Correlated Fermi Gas Model Skip to main content Learn about arXiv becoming an independent nonprofit. We gratefully acknowledge support from the Simons Foundation, member institutions , and all contributors. Donate > hep-ph > arXiv:2412.19810 Help | Advanced Search All fields Title Author Abstract Comments Journal reference ACM classification MSC classification Report number arXiv identifier DOI ORCID arXiv author ID Help pages Full text Search open search GO open navigation menu quick links Login Help Pages About --> High Energy Physics - Phenomenology arXiv:2412.19810 (hep-ph) [Submitted on 27 Nov 2024 ( v1 ), last revised 9 Jan 2025 (this version, v2)] Title: Quasielastic Lepton-Nucleus Scattering and the Correlated Fermi Gas Model Authors: Sam Carey View a PDF of the paper titled Quasielastic Lepton-Nucleus Scattering and the Correlated Fermi Gas Model, by Sam Carey View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: The study of neutrino-nucleus scattering processes is important for the new generation neutrino experiments for better understanding of the neutrino oscillation phenomenon. A significant source of uncertainty in the cross-section comes from limitations in our knowledge of nucleon and nuclear effects in the scattering process. Here we present a fully analytic implementation of the Correlated Fermi Gas nuclear model for the quasi-elastic lepton nucleus scattering. The implementation is then used to separately compare form factor effects and nuclear model effects, specifically the Relativistic Fermi Gas nuclear model, for both electron-carbon and neutrino-carbon scattering data. Comments: Contribution to the 25th International Workshop on Neutrinos from Accelerators Subjects: High Energy Physics - Phenomenology (hep-ph) Cite as: arXiv:2412.19810 [hep-ph] (or arXiv:2412.19810v2 [hep-ph] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2412.19810 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Sam Carey [ view email ] [v1] Wed, 27 Nov 2024 04:50:48 UTC (549 KB) [v2] Thu, 9 Jan 2025 14:09:24 UTC (549 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Quasielastic Lepton-Nucleus Scattering and the Correlated Fermi Gas Model, by Sam Carey View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source view license Current browse context: hep-ph < prev | next > new | recent | 2024-12 References & Citations INSPIRE HEP NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading... BibTeX formatted citation × loading... Data provided by: Bookmark Bibliographic Tools Bibliographic and Citation Tools Bibliographic Explorer Toggle Bibliographic Explorer ( What is the Explorer? ) Connected Papers Toggle Connected Papers ( What is Connected Papers? ) Litmaps Toggle Litmaps ( What is Litmaps? ) scite.ai Toggle scite Smart Citations ( What are Smart Citations? ) Code, Data, Media Code, Data and Media Associated with this Article alphaXiv Toggle alphaXiv ( What is alphaXiv? ) Links to Code Toggle CatalyzeX Code Finder for Paper